                        <h5 class="mbr-section-title card-title mbr-fonts-style align-center m-0 display-5"><strong>Emmanuel Okeke</strong></h5>
                        <h6 class="mbr-role mbr-fonts-style align-center mb-3 display-4"><strong><br></strong><br><strong>Head, Molecular Diagnostics and Research Unit</strong><br><br><strong>B. Tech, General Biotechnology</strong></h6>
                        <p class="card-text mbr-fonts-style align-center display-7">Emmanuel is a distinguished Biotechnologist who has garnered vastly consistent skill sets in molecular techniques with the ability to easily unlearn and learn.<br><br>Safety first as they say, having worked in biosafety level I – III molecular laboratories with biological safety cabinet classes I – III and manipulating samples and microorganisms in risk group I – III, he has extensive knowledge of biocontainment and functionality of biological safety cabinets.<br><br>Emmanuel has outstanding skills in nucleic acid extraction from various sample types on both manual and automated platforms using different extraction methods. His manual extraction skills are almost if not better than automated extractor machines.<br><br>So far, he has extracted and amplified about thirty thousand (30,000) samples with impeccable record of contamination free, precise and reproducible results. Emmanuel has in-depth experience in invasive pre-natal molecular testing, molecular foetal gender determination, molecular pathology (infectious diseases), molecular genetics, molecular onco-haematology and oncology using downstream processes such as standard PCR, qPCR, RT-PCR (one-step and two-step), RT-qPCR, multiplex qPCR, nested qPCR, AFLP, RFLP, VNTR, and Agarose gel electrophoresis.<br><br>Additionally, he is good at molecular lab setup, troubleshooting, reagent validation, process optimization, RT cycler validation, and post qPCR modifications. Emmanuel has trained students, other professionals, lecturers, PhD holders and professor in different molecular techniques.<br><br>He is particularly interested in the less than 1% of human genome that makes us different from one another, research, reagent optimization, protein engineering, synthetic biology and the omics.</p>
